It seems like all you need is &quot;observability&quot; (i.e. the opportunity to respond to changes in the data structure). The JavaFX interfaces `ObservableList`, `ObservableMap`, and `ObservableSet` are the direct *observable* equivalents of the standard `java.util` collections interfaces `List`, `Map`, and `Set`, respectively. So I think all you need here is an `ObservableList` (`List` being the collection interface which most closely mimics an array).

You can do something like:

```
public class Model {

    private final ObservableList&lt;Byte&gt; bytes ;

    public Model(byte[] bytes) {
        this.bytes = FXCollections.observableArrayList();
        for (byte b : bytes) this.bytes.add(b();
    }

    public void setByte(int index, byte b) {
        bytes.set(index, b);
    }

    public void getByte(int index) {
        return bytes.get(index);
    }

    public ObservableList&lt;Byte&gt; getBytes() {
        // prevent things like getBytes().add() etc.
        return FXCollections.unmodifiableObservableList(bytes);
    }

    public byte[] getBytesAsArray() {
        byte[] byteArray = new byte[bytes.size()];
        for (int i = 0 ; i &lt; bytes.size(); i++) {
            byteArray[i] = bytes.get(i);
        }
        return byteArray;
    }
}
```

and then 

```
myModel.getBytes().addListener((ListChangeListener.Change&lt;Byte&gt; change) -&gt; {
   // ...
});
```

See the [`ListChangeListener.Change` documentation](https://openjfx.io/javadoc/21/javafx.base/javafx/collections/ListChangeListener.Change.html) for more information.

The exact API in the `Model` class may need to be modified for whatever your actual use case is.

